segments.text: I think it had a lot to do with the faculty.
And we had a great faculty relationship.
I was never denied any sort of advising that I felt that I needed.
I was guided quite well.
Now, too, you've got to add to that the question
even with the tremendous growth that the university population experienced during that time.
Needless to say, the faculty pace could not keep up with it in terms of student-teacher ratio.
But most of the colleges, some better than others, did a great job of making it work anyway.
And there was, I mean, I don't know of a time

that I needed to either go see a professor in one of my classes, or excuse me, I cannot remember a time that I needed to go to see one of my professors or to see my academic advisor or to see a dean or an associate dean even before I became student body president that I was ever denied.
And it just wasn't a problem.
Now my perception was that A&M was working then to be inclusive
not to divide up into special categories.
Like I've said to people, and tell me if you agree or disagree, I've said to people, the real important thing was not what someone's ancestry was, but were you a part of A&M?
I had the impression that Jewish kids, Hispanic kids, Lebanese kids, in terms of parentage, all felt part of the group.
I'll say yes and no.
And the reason I'll say yes and no is sort of the fog.
You'll have to reel back, I think, about 8 to 10 years before 1976.
And so let's talk about when I may be 10 years, maybe less than that, about 68, that time frame.
Texas had just gone through, during that time frame, from 65 to 70.
and even as late as 71 in some instances, forced desegregation.

And particularly in towns where there were large minority populations, and that generally is the case as it remains today, sort of like east of Interstate 35, you had had some changes that had taken place.
And so these are the kinds of kids, now that you've got at the university environment,
I've always made an argument that supported the argument that kids were ready to make the join the, uh, maybe not some of the parents.
And so these are the type of kids that you end up having, but they're mixed in with kids from the other part of the state.
The western half of the state where
mixed race populations are not as great.
You've got these sort of new experiences going on.
Notwithstanding the collectivism that took place as a result of the Civil Rights Movement, by the time you got to about 74, 75, there was a change, in my view, on the part of
that population that was beginning to move back into a separatist, separateness, looking for an identity, if you will.
And so when you got, you know, everybody who was just amongst blacks, for example, there was this thing called the Black Awareness Committee.
The primary purpose of the Black Awareness Committee was for the purpose of bringing
maybe once a year, somebody who was a prominent black political leader or writer or author or whatever to campus for an event.
But the Black Awareness Committee also became a social organization.
It also became an activist organization.
in the sense of if there were issues that the Black Awareness Committee thought needed to be brought to the attention of the administration, that a lot of these ideas, if any, flowed from that group.
And it wasn't necessarily, I'm trying to think of some issues, but it wasn't necessarily because people had been denied things.
or that people thought that they were being discriminated against.
It was more along the lines of, you know, we need to have more opportunities to do this, so help us do that.
And so that sort of became, that was sort of the beginning, I think, of sort of the move back to divisiveness.
It wasn't necessarily promoted by the university, but it was more promoted by what I saw happening sociologically during that time frame.
Well, I think we have it now, today.
I think a great deal of it today.
And it's sort of matured in the 80s.
And so, what had been a forced, what had started out as we've been discriminated against, separate but equal, doesn't work, and all that kind of stuff.
And the courts say, okay, we're gonna force you to be equal and we're gonna lump you all together.
and everybody's going to get along, and everybody's going to figure out whose badges they're going to use, and all this kind of stuff.
When we start getting toward the mid-'70s and late-'70s, the war was over.
So the draft was gone.
So these other types of things that generally can sap the emotions and the thought processes of people.
That distraction wasn't there anymore.
And so I think that that was, even at conservative Texas A&M, that that was what was developing during that time.
Did any of the other minority students, be they black, Hispanic, or otherwise, did any of them ever come and fuss at you for not doing something they wanted done?
I don't remember that happening at all.
Good.
I got fussed at for other things.
Let's see.
I was taken before the judicial board while I was student body president.
For?
Failure to implement a piece of legislation that the previous student senate had enacted.
The previous student senate had enacted because of the guy who'd been...
academic affairs vice president, a piece of legislation which required that students be given the opportunity to vote confidence or no confidence in members of the faculty.

And that this was to be published by student government for the purpose of students being able to decide with more scientifically gathered information, of course, the quality of the professors as they chose courses.
I was supposed to have done this.
The way the legislation was written, it was written such that it had to be done during the fall semester of the particular academic year.
And we still going?
Of the particular academic year.
You know, on Monday I started classes, so it was.
So you enrolled the second?
Second summer session.
Second summer session.
So I'd already been a fish by the time fish camp came around.
Did you and your buddy, freshman buddies, did you all start using Aggie slang quickly?
Were you fish?
No, not really.
As I think back to those days, a lot of that had to do with the fact that
Number one, I wasn't in the core.
And the core during that time frame really had more of the slang associated with being a fish and all that kind of stuff than did the non-rec population on campus.
For example, now the freshmen who are chosen in student government to be aides, if you will, during their first year on campus are called fish aides.
Back in 1973, that wasn't the case.
So more of the fish aspect and other Aggie slang was more associated with being in the Corps of Cadets than it was otherwise.
on campus.
Let's jump now to September.
And you're taking a full load, I presume.
Describe a typical freshman academic day.
It began when?
Oh, I generally loaded it on pretty well, because what I was trying to do was, after having taken a year off, it was my goal and objective to
complete my undergraduate degree pretty close to as well I could those who would have normally started with me in the fall of 1972 had I not done the FFA thing.
So I probably was taking 16 to 18 hours and, you know, again, the beginning of the day and worked my way through the end of the day.
One of
One of the anecdotes that I was going to mention, I distinctly remember, in fact, that's about the only course I remember from my freshman year.
No, that's not true.
I do remember this one.
There was a new guy on campus in the chemistry department at that period in time who was teaching freshman chemistry named Rod O'Connor.
And Rod had written, that was during the time frame that
Program learning was sort of like a new thing, at least at the secondary school level.

And Rod decided that he was going to write a freshman chemistry text that was based on a programmed learning concept, which basically is you sort of like take chapters of stuff and have self-tests associated with each chapter and the sort of building process that goes on in the program learning
aspect of it.
And Rod had written this chemistry book.
And actually, I remember it quite well because it had been typed and had been reduced in size to the size of a book and had been bound.
And that was a textbook that we used.
It was over in the old chemistry building.
There were, I guess, a couple of hundred of us and freshmen in the class taking the introductory chemistry course.
And I remember distinctly going into the room that fall and probably 10 at the most
of the 200 or so students had calculators.
And of course, there are a lot of numbers associated with the way Rod had designed this freshman course.
And there were about, oh, I guess, 80% of us who either had access to or knew how to use a slide rule.
So Rod, in an effort to sort of have fairness, wouldn't let the guys using the calculators use their calculators in class

But he got graduate assistants to do special tutoring sessions to teach us, those who did not know how to use a slide rule, how to use a slide rule so that they could compete effectively and learn in a classroom environment.
That's one of the interesting experiences about my first year there.
I can understand Rod making the decision not to,
allow the four or five kids or 10 kids who had calculators to use them.

Uh, but for him to take the added step of, of going the extra mile to teach those kids who did not have knowledge of the slide rule use so that they could could compete effectively and learn in the, in that, in that learning environment, uh, I think is a great attestation to the nature of the relationships that existed during that time.
between faculty and students.
At the time, the university probably was about the size, oh, about 14,000 kids, roughly.
And even then, we still had some large classes, particularly in basic chemistry and some of the other courses that we took, history classes, for example.
But that extra effort, I think, on Ron's part was indicative of the pretty much

across the board attitude of faculty in terms of their relationship with students and that I think is a great compliment and that is something that I hope will never be lost in the learning environment at Texas A&M.
One year later ironically that year still sort of broken up for me because in October I was elected national FFA secretary and
dropped out of school.
So at the end of your first semester?
Not even at the end, I dropped out mid-semester.
Oh, okay.

I dropped out mid-semester, so now I've only had like one summer session under my belt and about six weeks of undergraduate, I mean of what would have been the start of my, or continuation of my freshman year, whichever, but my first full-time load, if you will.
And I took incompletes in all of my courses
and traveled around the country for a year as National FFA Secretary.
I re-enrolled at Texas A&M in the fall of 1974, and now with a big whopping one summer session under my belt and two years behind my classmates from high school years,
And re-enrolled, fortunately, in the classes worked in each of the classes that I had taken incompletes in the year before.

And I want to reel forward to that chemistry class again because when I arrived in the chemistry class the fall of 1974 to finally hopefully complete chemistry 101, 95% of the kids in the class had calculators and probably 5% of them
We're still using the slide room, which I think is a tremendous example of the advent of technology in one short year.
And it's a very vivid reminder to me of how quickly things can change, particularly now.
You get a free calculator that's solar powered for doing a subscription to a magazine.
And so that was finally, I got re-enrolled
in the school at Texas A&M in the fall of 74.
At that time I also came back and changed my major, or at least I did at the end of that first semester of 1974 when I was in biochemistry and changed my major to agricultural economics.
What led you to make that change?
I made the decision that throughout the course of that year that I served as
Well, one could make the argument that calculus and the perspective of doing organic chemistry was what made me make that change.
That was not.
But what I decided over the course of the year while I was serving as National FFA Secretary was that I did not want to be a biochemist because of the options that it provided for me.
I was either going to teach, which I didn't think was something that I wanted to do, or I would be engaged in
some really neat, pure scientific research, which I decided wasn't my cup of tea.
And I ultimately decided I did not want to be a physician.
But I decided that perhaps a better role for me, knowing myself a little bit better at that time, would be one which allowed me to have more interaction with people, but in a verbal sort of a sense.
And I got this idea that I might want to go to law school.
And so the course of instruction
that I chose was economics because I had gotten a tremendous amount of exposure to the agribusiness world while I was serving as national secretary.
And so I made the swap.
Was there an academic advisor or advisors at A&M that helped you?
Well, Dr. Brown was sort of my buddy during that time frame, needs to say, because of our relationship that we had developed going back to my early FFA days, when I was in high school, actually.
That sort of shifted when I made the transition to Ag Eco to Dr. J.C. Grady, who was my undergraduate advisor, if you will, for the remainder of my academic time at A&M.
Also in that bunch was, and this was sort of because of a job that I had, I was a student worker in the

early, very earliest days of the, what is now known as the real estate center, which was then the Texas real estate research center, which had sort of been a collaboration created primarily by the professors in the economics department who were making a transition from sort of the rural side of the program to more of the, um, uh, urban side of, of, of real estate and real estate development.
And, uh,
A former head of the Department of Ag Economics, Dr. Pat Rudin, A.B.
Pat Rudin, was the first director of the Real Estate Center.

One of the other professors who was doing double duty with the Extension Service, or I guess triple duty, the Extension Service, the Research Center, and also in the Department of Agriculture and Economics was a guy named Don Levi.
And Don is a lawyer, had written an agricultural law text.

And since I'd kind of gotten into this thought that I might want to be a lawyer, Don and JC Grady were sort of my mentors, if you will, in terms of the guidance that they gave me during my time at A&M.
And then there was this associate dean over at the College of Agriculture named R.C.
Potts who sort of overrode it all.
Because I had the impression Dean Potts
had a special role in a lot of students.
He did.
He did.
He did.
And I'll tell a story about that later.
I'm gathering that because you did not start out as a freshman three months out of high school, that being a part of a certain class didn't matter like it would have if you'd been over in the Corps.
That was one of the reasons, in fact, that I chose not to be in the Corps.
In fact, that's probably the only reason that I chose not to be in the Corps.

I felt very strongly then, and I do to this day, that the leadership laboratory created by the Corps of Cadets at Texas A&M University is one which is predicated upon a group of people moving together through similar experiences, even though
They may be in different undergraduate curriculum.
Nonetheless, the movement together and the camaraderie that is developed during that leadership experience is vital for the Corps of Cadets' continued vitality as a part of Texas A&M University.
I couldn't get that.
I couldn't get that because I was trying to catch up with my buddies who were my age, if you will.
And trying to frog into the Corps as a junior was not going to cut it.
And so as a result, I opted not to be in the Corps of Cadets.
But as I kidded all of my colleagues later when I became student body president, I was nonetheless commander in chief, which included the Corps of Cadets.
OK, who were the advisors, teachers, et cetera, that helped to get you involved in A&M leadership experiences?
Well, actually, there weren't any folks involved in that.
It was sort of like, I guess, what one would consider sort of expected of me, and I sort of expected it of myself.
And so it was really sort of weird because, let me see how I describe this, if I can get these dates and times right.
In the fall of 1973, we had freshman senator elections.
And I chose to run for freshman College of Agriculture senator.
But it was basically amongst the folks in the class of 1977 as opposed to 76 because I had been out for a year.
And I didn't really need a whole lot of encouragement in that regard.
And secondly, I had a pretty good likely voter base in my favor because of
the decision as to who is freshman agriculture senator is made by freshman College of Agriculture majors, many of whom I had known for four or five years because of my involvement in FFA.
So it was sort of a pretty easy choice.
Ironically, though, I had to relinquish that position six weeks later, or three weeks later, whatever it was, when I dropped out of school.
When I came back to school in the fall of 1974,

In the spring of 1975, when normal student body elections were held, I ran for, it was really sort of hard to figure out which one I was supposed to run for because my hours were really sort of screwed up, and I ran for College of Agriculture.
What did I have?
I think I had enough hours to be a sophomore.
So I think it was sophomore.
In the spring of 75, and I was elected from the College of Agriculture.
Did you campaign?
Not really.
You didn't go around and shake hands?
No, I didn't go around and shake hands.
I didn't do any of those things.
It was sort of like go to a couple of the College of Agriculture meetings like the Collegiate FFA or the Animal Science, I mean the Saddle and Sirloin Bunch or whatever.
But basically I had a lot of friends spreading the word.
We put up some flyers and, you know, that's sort of it.
So I was elected in the spring to be a member of,

the Senate from the College of Agriculture and at the end of that spring of 75 that new group elects officers for the following year within or at the time within the Senate and I ran for Speaker of the Student Senate and was elected Speaker in 75.
So that would be for your
Junior year.
Basically.
It really never got straight because that was, I guess I served as speaker during the fall of 1975 in the academic year of 75, 76.
And it was at the end of or in the spring of 1976 that I ran for student body president and was elected in April of that year.
And I served as student body president
the 76-77 academic year, but I actually graduated and received my undergraduate degree in December of 1976.
Now that's another one too, but this is another Dr. Potts story.
It was sort of like, during that time, and I'll just spring back and forth on these and we can clean them up later, but during that time, graduating seniors did not have to take finals.
assuming you were passing at that time.
And so you basically finished your last round of quizzes like in November around about Thanksgiving.
And so I was kind of done and having a great time hanging out at College Station, bothering all of my friends and keeping them from studying those who were not graduating in December.
And during, let's see, that year I was also serving as chairman of the sportsmanship committee for
the Southwest Conference Athletic Association.
The guy who was then Corps commander who actually succeeded me as student body president was a guy named Robert Harvey.

And Bob and I sort of became good friends because I made a concerted effort during my tenure as student body president to reach out to the Corps, again going back to those things I said earlier about the vibrancy of the university and its heart and soul and how the Corps of Cadets provides a tremendous
boost in that regard.
And I had to come present the sportsmanship committee here at the Cotton Bowl.
Yet A&M was playing Florida in the Sun Bowl.
And so Bob and I came up here first, kind of did the thing at the Cotton Bowl, and then we went out to El Paso, did the Sun Bowl, and went back to a basketball game at College Station, ironically.
So we made a big old tour of Texas.
But sometime during that time frame, and it's like,
I guess because of the energy crisis, school was starting later.
I believe we had taken a longer break for Christmas, New Year's recess.
And I'm kind of like hanging out finally and getting ready to come back down here.
And I get this phone call from Dr. Potts.
And it's like out of clear blue, we're doing the holidays.
And I said, Dr. Potts, how you doing?
Blah, blah, blah.
Have a good holiday.
Get through all of the pleasantries.
And he says, Fred, do you enjoy being student vice president?
And I said, I love it, Dr. Potts, you know, it's going to come to an end here in the spring, but yeah, I love it.
He goes, well, do you realize that to be student body president, you have to be enrolled as a student?
And I said, yeah.
He goes, well, didn't you just graduate in December?
Well, yeah, I did.
He says, well, like, how are you going to be a student in the spring?
You know, so like, oh.
So as a result, I was immediately enrolled into college.
the graduate program in agricultural economics, seeking an MS degree so that I could be a student while I finished my term as student vice president.
Thanks to Dr. Potts, I didn't get sort of removed from office for lack of being a student.
So again, one of the great, unique, wonderful things about the relationships between students and professors
going up to the dean's office and, of course, ultimately into the administration, higher vice presidents and presidents.

Were it not for that kind of attention that was paid to all students, not just those of us who happen to be involved in leadership positions within the student government or whatever, or on campus in other student leadership roles, that thing is that which is most unique.

And now I'm talking about a time frame when our university had been the fastest growing state public institution in the country for the previous two years and what had been 14,000 students that I mentioned earlier was now 28,000 students.
But that personal relationship stuff continued and that's very unique and very special.
Why do you think it was growing so fast right then?
I think it was growing quickly then for
Oh, I think the primary reason was that all of a sudden, uh, Texas A&M, uh, did not have as much of an agrarian, uh, image.
And that image was changing.
Frankly, I'd seen that changing though, even going back to my days in FFA, you know, at the time that I was national FFA secretary, the largest FFA chapter in the country.
was in downtown Los Angeles.
It was horticulture programs, except these guys not only had horticulture, but they also had an acre where they raised cattle in downtown, which is the most unusual experience.
But there was a huge shift going on in the agribusiness side.
Of course, the College of Agriculture was still, along with the College of Engineering, sort of the largest two colleges within the university during that time frame.
And as the ag programs began to shift,
What happened was that I think the image that A&M had previously had, which was like all corps and all military and straight, pure agriculture, farm boys and girls, was changing.
In addition, females started coming to school.
And that was the other factor.
I may be going out on a limb, but I am going to guess that
Probably during my last year, and of course these numbers can be found, but I'm going to say, you know, we didn't have just a whole lot of females at college even in 1976.
See, Williams made the board agree before he accepted the job that he could take an existing dormitory
And on January 1, 1971,
